Boston Airbnb Data Analysis¶

Analyzing the airbnb data for boston and understanding some important business questions...

The dataset contains calendar availability for each of these listings and user reviews on the listings.

The CRISP-DM Process (Cross Industry Process for Data Mining)¶

It is a data mining process followed in the industry and contains the following steps:

  1. Business Understanding - Understanding important business objectives that we will solve by analyzing the data.
  2. Data Understanding - Understading the data available, identifying subsets of required data and understanding quality problems in data.
  3. Prepare Data - This includes activities line data cleaning, data wrangling, etc. to prepare final datasets required for analysis.
  4. Model Data - This technique use data modeling techniques like neural nets which makes data easier to read and helps with clear analysis and processing.
  5. Results - Models made in above steps are tested here and results are examined if they will work properly on training data.
  6. Deploy - This include deployment of model on unseen data, and create new mechanisms to deal with new data to find solutions for business objectives.

Business Understanding¶

  • Which is the most reviewed and rated places to stay in Boston?
  • What is the airbnb price variation in the city and find some of the cheapest places to stay in Boston?
  • How Airbnb prices have varied over time in last two year in Boston?

In [23]:
# removing '$' and ',' symbols from price column in df_calendar and df_listings dataframes
# converting prices in price columns in df_calendar and df_listings dataframes from str to float
# removing the null values from review_scores_value columns in df_listings dataframe


df_calendar[['price']] = df_calendar[['price']].replace('[\$,]','',regex=True).astype(float)
df_calendar = df_calendar.dropna()

df_listings.price = df_listings.price.str.replace('$', '').str.replace(',', '')
df_listings['price'] = df_listings['price'].astype(float)

df_listings = df_listings.dropna(subset=['review_scores_value'])


df_listings["review_scores_value"].isnull().mean()
df_listings = df_listings[~df_listings["review_scores_value"].isnull()]

Data Visualization¶

In [28]:
def plot_func(df, group_by, column, operation, title, x_label, y_label):
    
    '''
    Function: for plotting bar graphs
    INPUT:
    df: dataframe
    group_by: column you want to group the data by
    column: feature to be ploted against groupby data
    operation: aggregate operation made on column
    title: Title of bar plot
    x_label: x-axis label
    y_label: y-axis label
    OUTPUT: Plot of data
    '''
    
    df.groupby(group_by)[column].agg(operation).plot.bar(figsize =(10,5),title = title)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)
